            &lt;/div&gt;

            &lt;div class=&quot;comment-body js-comment-edit-hide&quot;&gt;

                &lt;span class=&quot;comment-copy&quot;&gt;As noted in the &lt;a href=&quot;http://stackoverflow.com/a/11710573/15168&quot;&gt;answer&lt;/a&gt; by &lt;a href=&quot;http://stackoverflow.com/users/418413/kojiro&quot;&gt;kojiro&lt;/a&gt;, it is perfectly possible and legal to start the pipeline with &lt;code&gt;&amp;lt; file command1 ...&lt;/code&gt;.  Although the conventional position for the I/O redirection operators is after the command name and its arguments, that is only the convention and not a mandatory placement.  The &lt;code&gt;&amp;lt;&lt;/code&gt; does have to precede the file name.  So, there&apos;s a close to perfect symmetry between &lt;code&gt;&amp;gt;output&lt;/code&gt; and &lt;code&gt;&amp;lt;input&lt;/code&gt; redirections: &lt;code&gt;&amp;lt;input command1 -opt 1 | command2 -o | command3 &amp;gt;output&lt;/code&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;

