            &lt;/div&gt;

            &lt;div class=&quot;comment-body js-comment-edit-hide&quot;&gt;

                &lt;span class=&quot;comment-copy&quot;&gt;The rule of thumb I&apos;ve adopted for deciding where the STDIN redirect goes is to do whatever minimizes the &lt;i&gt;appearance&lt;/i&gt; of ambiguity/ &lt;i&gt;potential&lt;/i&gt; for surprise. Dogmatically saying it goes before brings up necromancer&apos;s issue, but dogmatically saying it goes after &lt;i&gt;can&lt;/i&gt; do the same thing. Consider: &lt;code&gt;stdout=$(foo bar -exec baz &amp;lt;qux | ENV=VAR quux)&lt;/code&gt;. Q. Does &lt;code&gt;&amp;lt;qux&lt;/code&gt; apply to &lt;code&gt;foo&lt;/code&gt;, or to &lt;code&gt;baz&lt;/code&gt;, which is &lt;code&gt;-exec&lt;/code&gt;&apos;d by &lt;code&gt;foo&lt;/code&gt;? A. It applies to &lt;code&gt;foo&lt;/code&gt;, but &lt;i&gt;can&lt;/i&gt; appear ambiguous. Putting &lt;code&gt;&amp;lt;qux&lt;/code&gt; &lt;i&gt;before&lt;/i&gt; &lt;code&gt;foo&lt;/code&gt; in this case is more clear, albeit less common, and is analogous to the trailing &lt;code&gt;ENV=VAR quux&lt;/code&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;

